# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: power-supply-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:power-supply-design/load-regulation] For a constant-current supply, the above equation uses currents instead of voltages, and the maximum and minimum load values are when the largest and smallest specified voltage across the load are produced.
[src:power-supply-design/load-regulation] For switching power supplies, the primary source of regulation error is switching ripple, rather than control loop precision.
[src:power-supply-design/load-regulation] In such cases, load regulation is defined without normalizing to voltage at nominal load and has the unit of volts, not a percentage.
[src:power-supply-design/load-regulation] A simple way to manually measure load regulation is to connect three parallel load resistors to the power supply where two of the resistors, R2 and R3, are connected through switches while the other resistor, R1 is connected directly.
[src:power-supply-design/load-regulation] The values of the resistors are selected such that R1 gives the highest load resistance, R1||R2 gives the nominal load resistance and either R1||R2||R3 or R2||R3 gives the lowest load resistance.
[src:power-supply-design/load-regulation] A voltmeter is then connected in parallel to the resistors and the measured values of voltage for each load state can be used to calculate the load regulation as given in the equation above.
[src:power-supply-design/load-regulation] Programmable loads are typically used to automate the measurement of load regulation.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A **power supply** is an electrical device that supplies electric power to an electrical load.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The main purpose of a power supply is to convert electric current from a source to the correct voltage, current, and frequency to power the load.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] As a result, power supplies are sometimes referred to as electric power converters.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some power supplies are separate standalone pieces of equipment, while others are built into the load appliances that they power.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Examples of the latter include power supplies found in desktop computers and consumer electronics devices.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] All power supplies have a *power input* connection, which receives energy in the form of electric current from a source, and one or more *power output* or **power rail** connections that deliver current to the load.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The source power may come from the electric power grid, such as an electrical outlet, energy storage devices such as batteries or fuel cells, generators or alternators, solar power converters, or another power supply.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The input and output are usually hardwired circuit connections, though some power supplies employ wireless energy transfer to power their loads without wired connections.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some power supplies have other types of inputs and outputs as well, for functions such as external monitoring and control.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power supplies are categorized in various ways, including by functional features.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] For example, a *regulated* power supply is one that maintains constant output voltage or current despite variations in load current or input voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Conversely, the output of an *unregulated* power supply can change significantly when its input voltage or load current changes.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] *Adjustable* power supplies allow the output voltage or current to be programmed by mechanical controls (e.g., knobs on the power supply front panel), or by means of a control input, or both.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An *adjustable regulated* power supply is one that is both adjustable and regulated.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An *isolated* power supply has a power output that is electrically independent of its power input; this is in contrast to other power supplies that share a common connection between power input and output.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power supplies are packaged in different ways and classified accordingly.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A *bench* power supply is a stand-alone desktop unit used in applications such as circuit test and development.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] *Open frame* power supplies have only a partial mechanical enclosure, sometimes consisting of only a mounting base; these are typically built into machinery or other equipment.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] *Rack mount* power supplies are designed to be secured into standard electronic equipment racks.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An *integrated* power supply is one that shares a common printed circuit board with its load.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An *external* power supply, *AC adapter* or *power brick*, is a power supply located in the load's AC power cord that plugs into a wall outlet; a *wall wart* is an external supply integrated with the outlet plug itself.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] These are popular in consumer electronics because of their safety; the hazardous 120- or 240-volt main current is transformed down to a safer voltage before it enters the appliance body.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power supplies can be broadly divided into *linear* and *switching* types.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Linear power converters process the input power directly, with all active power conversion components operating in their linear operating regions.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In switching power converters, the input power is converted to AC or to DC pulses before processing, by components that operate predominantly in non-linear modes (e.g., transistors that spend most of their time in cutoff or saturation).
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power is "lost" (converted to heat) when components operate in their linear regions and, consequently, switching converters are usually more efficient than linear converters because their components spend less time in linear operating regions.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power supplies are sometimes categorized according to their intended purpose, such as "AC-DC front end for grid bias" or "DC-DC converter for point-of-load (POL) regulation".
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An AC-to-DC power supply operates on an AC input voltage and generates a DC output voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Depending on the application requirements, the output voltage may contain varying amounts of AC frequency components, known as ripple voltage, which are influenced by the AC input voltage frequency and the power supply's operation.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A DC power supply operating on DC input voltage is called a DC-to-DC converter.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] This section focuses mostly on the AC-to-DC variant.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In a linear power supply, the AC input voltage first passes through a power transformer, then undergoes rectification and filtering to produce a DC voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Filtering minimizes the AC mains frequency component present in the rectifier output.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] It can be as simple as a single capacitor or as complex as a pi filter.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The required level of filtering in the power supply depends on the electric load's tolerance to ripple.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In some applications, ripple can be entirely ignored.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] For instance, in certain battery charging applications, the power supply may consist only of a transformer and a diode, with a resistor at the output to limit the charging current.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In a switched-mode power supply (SMPS), the AC mains input is directly rectified and then filtered to obtain a DC voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The resulting DC voltage is then switched on and off at a high frequency by electronic switching circuitry, thus producing an AC current that will pass through a high-frequency transformer or inductor.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Switching occurs at a very high frequency (typically 10 kHz — 1 MHz), thereby enabling the use of transformers and filter capacitors that are much smaller, lighter, and less expensive than those found in linear power supplies operating at mains frequency.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] After the inductor or transformer secondary, the high frequency AC is rectified and filtered to produce the DC output voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] If the SMPS uses an adequately insulated high-frequency transformer, the output will be electrically isolated from the mains; this feature is often essential for safety.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Switched-mode power supplies are usually regulated, and to keep the output voltage constant, the power supply employs a feedback controller that monitors current drawn by the load.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The switching duty cycle increases as power output requirements increase.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] SMPSs often include safety features such as current limiting or a crowbar circuit to help protect the device and the user from harm.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In the event that an abnormal high-current power draw is detected, the switched-mode supply can assume this is a direct short and will shut itself down before damage is done.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] PC power supplies often provide a *power good* signal to the motherboard; the absence of this signal prevents operation when abnormal supply voltages are present.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some SMPSs have an absolute limit on their minimum current output.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] They are only able to output above a certain power level and cannot function below that point.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In a no-load condition the frequency of the power slicing circuit increases to great speed, causing the isolated transformer to act as a Tesla coil, causing damage due to the resulting very high voltage power spikes.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Switched-mode supplies with protection circuits may briefly turn on but then shut down when no load has been detected.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A very small low-power dummy load such as a ceramic power resistor or 10-watt light bulb can be attached to the supply to allow it to run with no primary load attached.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The switch-mode power supplies used in computers have historically had low power factors and have also been significant sources of line interference (due to induced power line harmonics and transients).
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In simple switch-mode power supplies, the input stage may distort the line voltage waveform, which can adversely affect other loads (and result in poor power quality for other utility customers), and cause unnecessary heating in wires and distribution equipment.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Furthermore, customers incur higher electric bills when operating lower power factor loads.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] To circumvent these problems, some computer switch-mode power supplies perform power factor correction, and may employ input filters or additional switching stages to reduce line interference.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A capacitive power supply (transformerless power supply) uses the reactance of a capacitor to reduce the mains voltage to a smaller AC voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Typically, the resulting reduced AC voltage is then rectified, filtered and regulated to produce a constant DC output voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The output voltage is not isolated from the mains.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Consequently, to avoid exposing people and equipment from hazardous high voltage, anything connected to the power supply must be reliably insulated.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The voltage reduction capacitor must withstand the full mains voltage, and it must also have enough capacitance to support maximum load current at the rated output voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Taken together, these constraints limit practical uses of this type of supply to low-power applications.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The function of a *linear voltage regulator* is to convert a varying DC voltage to a constant, often specific, lower DC voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In addition, they often provide a current limiting function to protect the power supply and load from *overcurrent* (excessive, potentially destructive current).
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A constant output voltage is required in many power supply applications, but the voltage provided by many energy sources will vary with changes in load impedance.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Furthermore, when an unregulated DC power supply is the energy source, its output voltage will also vary with changing input voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] To circumvent this, some power supplies use a linear voltage regulator to maintain the output voltage at a steady value, independent of fluctuations in input voltage and load impedance.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Linear regulators can also reduce the magnitude of ripple and noise on the output voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An AC power supply typically takes the voltage from a wall outlet (mains supply) and uses a transformer to step up or step down the voltage to the desired voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In some cases, the source voltage is the same as the output voltage; this is called an isolation transformer.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Other AC power supply transformers do not provide mains isolation; these are called autotransformers; a variable output autotransformer is known as a variac.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Other kinds of AC power supplies are designed to provide a nearly constant current, and output voltage may vary depending on impedance of the load.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In cases when the power source is direct current, (like an automobile storage battery), an inverter and step-up transformer may be used to convert it to AC power.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Portable AC power may be provided by an alternator powered by a diesel or gasoline engine (for example, at a construction site, in an automobile or boat, or backup power generation for emergency services) whose current is passed to a regulator circuit to provide a constant voltage at the output.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some kinds of AC power conversion do not use a transformer.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] If the output voltage and input voltage are the same, and primary purpose of the device is to filter AC power, it may be called a line conditioner.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] If the device is designed to provide backup power, it may be called an uninterruptible power supply.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A circuit may be designed with a voltage multiplier topology to directly step-up AC power; formerly, such an application was a vacuum tube AC/DC receiver.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In modern use, AC power supplies can be divided into single phase and three phase systems.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] AC power Supplies can also be used to change the frequency as well as the voltage, they are often used by manufacturers to check the suitability of their products for use in other countries.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] 230 V 50 Hz or 115 60 Hz or even 400 Hz for avionics testing.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An AC adapter is a power supply built into an AC mains power plug.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] AC adapters are also known by various other names such as "plug pack" or "plug-in adapter", or by slang terms such as "wall wart".
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] AC adapters typically have a single AC or DC output that is conveyed over a hardwired cable to a connector, but some adapters have multiple outputs that may be conveyed over one or more cables.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] "Universal" AC adapters have interchangeable input connectors to accommodate different AC mains voltages.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Adapters with AC outputs may consist only of a passive transformer; in case of DC-output, adapters consist of either transformer with few diodes and capacitors or they may employ switch-mode power supply circuitry.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] AC adapters consume power (and produce electric and magnetic fields) even when not connected to a load; for this reason they are sometimes known as "electricity vampires", and may be plugged into power strips to allow them to be conveniently turned on and off.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A **programmable power supply** (PPS) is one that allows remote control of its operation through an analog input or digital interface such as RS-232 or GPIB.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Controlled properties may include voltage, current, and in the case of AC output power supplies, frequency.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] They are used in a wide variety of applications, including automated equipment testing, crystal growth monitoring, semiconductor fabrication, and x-ray generators.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Programmable power supplies typically employ an integral microcomputer to control and monitor power supply operation.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power supplies equipped with a computer interface may use proprietary communication protocols or standard protocols and device control languages such as SCPI.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] More recent implementations also provide Ethernet interfaces using TCP/IP or UDP, or Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) links carrying proprietary protocols to achieve deterministic, high-throughput control and monitoring.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Ethernet is today the most widespread solution, being cost-effective and simple to integrate with automated test benches.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] An uninterruptible power supply (UPS) takes its power from two or more sources simultaneously.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] It is usually powered directly from the AC mains, while simultaneously charging a storage battery.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Should there be a dropout or failure of the mains, the battery takes over sufficiently fast that the load never experiences an interruption.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] That definition is important because transmission of high speed data and communications service must have continuity of that service.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some manufacturers use a quasi-standard of 4 milliseconds.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] However, with high speed data even 4 ms of time in transitioning from one source to another is not fast enough.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The transition must be made in a break before make method.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The UPS meeting that requirement is referred to as a true UPS or a hybrid UPS.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] How much time the UPS will provide is most often based on batteries and in conjunction with generators.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] That time can range from 5 to 15 minutes to hours or even days.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] In many computer installations, it is only enough time on batteries to give the operators time to shut down the system in an orderly way.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Other UPS schemes may use an internal combustion engine or turbine to supply power during a utility power outage and the amount of battery time is then dependent upon how long it takes the generator to be on line and the criticality of the equipment served.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Such a scheme is found in hospitals, data centers, call centers, cell sites and central telephone offices.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A **high-voltage power supply** is one that outputs hundreds or thousands of volts.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A special output connector is used that prevents arcing, insulation breakdown and accidental human contact.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Federal Standard connectors are typically used for applications above 20 kV, though other types of connectors (e.g., SHV connector) may be used at lower voltages.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some high-voltage power supplies provide an analog input or digital communication interface that can be used to control the output voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] High-voltage power supplies are commonly used to accelerate and manipulate electron and ion beams in equipment such as x-ray generators, electron microscopes, and focused ion beam columns, and in a variety of other applications, including electrophoresis and electrostatics.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] High-voltage power supplies typically apply the bulk of their input energy to a power inverter, which in turn drives a voltage multiplier or a high turns ratio, high-voltage transformer, or both (usually a transformer followed by a multiplier) to produce high voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The high voltage is passed out of the power supply through the special connector and is also applied to a voltage divider that converts it to a low-voltage *metering* signal compatible with low-voltage circuitry.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The metering signal is used by a closed-loop controller that regulates the high voltage by controlling inverter input power, and it may also be conveyed out of the power supply to allow external circuitry to monitor the high-voltage output.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A bipolar power supply operates in all four quadrants of the voltage/current Cartesian plane, meaning that it will generate positive and negative voltages and currents as required to maintain regulation.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] When its output is controlled by a low-level analog signal, it is effectively a low-bandwidth operational amplifier with high output power and seamless zero-crossings.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] This type of power supply is commonly used to power magnetic devices in scientific applications.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The suitability of a particular power supply for an application is determined by various attributes of the power supply, which are typically listed in the power supply's *specification*.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The power supply of an electrical system tends to generate heat.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The higher the efficiency, the less heat is generated by the power supply.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] There are many ways to manage the heat of a power supply unit.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The types of cooling generally fall into two categories -- convection and conduction.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Common convection methods for cooling electronic power supplies include natural air flow, forced air flow, or other liquid flow over the unit.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Common conduction cooling methods include heat sinks, cold plates, and thermal compounds.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power supplies often have protection from short circuit or overload that could damage the supply or cause a fire.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Fuses and circuit breakers are two commonly used mechanisms for overload protection.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A fuse contains a short piece of wire which melts if too much current flows.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] This effectively disconnects the power supply from its load, and the equipment stops working until the problem that caused the overload is identified and the fuse is replaced.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some power supplies use a very thin wire link soldered in place as a fuse.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Fuses in power supply units may be replaceable by the end user, but fuses in consumer equipment may require tools to access and change.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A circuit breaker contains an element that heats, bends and triggers a spring which shuts the circuit down.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Once the element cools, and the problem is identified the breaker can be reset and the power restored.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some power supplies use a thermal cutout buried in the transformer rather than a fuse.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The advantage is it briefly allows greater current to be drawn than the maximum allowed continuous current.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some such cutouts are self resetting, some are single use only.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some supplies use current limiting instead of cutting off power if overloaded.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The two types of current limiting used are electronic limiting and impedance limiting.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The former is common on lab bench power supplies, the latter is common on supplies of less than 3 watts output.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A foldback current limiter reduces the output current to much less than the maximum non-fault current.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Power supplies are a fundamental component of many electronic devices and therefore used in a diverse range of applications.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] This list is a small sample of the many applications of power supplies.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A modern computer power supply is a switch-mode power supply that converts AC power from the mains supply, to several DC voltages.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Switch-mode supplies replaced linear supplies due to cost, weight, efficiency and size improvements.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The diverse collection of output voltages also have widely varying current draw requirements.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Electric vehicles are those which rely on energy created through electricity generation.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] A power supply unit is part of the necessary design to convert high voltage vehicle battery power.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Arc welding uses electricity to join metals by melting them.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] The electricity is provided by a *welding power supply*, and can either be AC or DC.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Arc welding requires high currents typically between 100 and 350 amperes.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Some types of welding can use as few as 10 amperes, while some applications of spot welding employ currents as high as 60,000 amperes for an extremely short time.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Welding power supplies consisted of transformers or engines driving generators; modern welding equipment uses semiconductors and may include microprocessor control.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] Both commercial and military avionic systems require either a DC-DC or AC/DC power supply to convert energy into usable voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] These may often operate at 400 Hz in the interest of weight savings.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] This refers to conveyors, assembly lines, bar code readers, cameras, motors, pumps, semi-fabricated manufacturing and more.
[src:power-supply-design/power-supply] These include ventilators, infusion pumps, surgical and dental instruments, imaging and beds.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Ripple (specifically **ripple current** or **surge current**) may also refer to the pulsed current consumption of non-linear devices like capacitor-input rectifiers.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] As well as these time-varying phenomena, there is a **frequency domain ripple** that arises in some classes of filter and other signal processing networks.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] In this case the periodic variation is a variation in the insertion loss of the network against increasing frequency.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The variation may not be strictly linearly periodic.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] In this meaning also, ripple is usually to be considered an incidental effect, its existence being a compromise between the amount of ripple and other design parameters.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Ripple is wasted power, and has many undesirable effects in a DC circuit: it heats components, causes noise and distortion, and may cause digital circuits to operate improperly.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Ripple may be reduced by an electronic filter, and eliminated by a voltage regulator.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A non-ideal DC voltage waveform can be viewed as a composite of a constant DC component (offset) with an alternating (AC) voltage—the ripple voltage—overlaid.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The ripple component is often small in magnitude relative to the DC component, but in absolute terms, ripple (as in the case of HVDC transmission systems) may be thousands of volts.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Ripple itself is a composite (non-sinusoidal) waveform consisting of harmonics of some fundamental frequency which is usually the original AC line frequency, but in the case of switched-mode power supplies, the fundamental frequency can be tens of kilohertz to megahertz.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The characteristics and components of ripple depend on its source: there is single-phase half- and full-wave rectification, and three-phase half- and full-wave rectification.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Rectification can be controlled (uses Silicon Controlled Rectifiers (SCRs)) or uncontrolled (uses diodes).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] There is in addition, active rectification which uses transistors.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Analogous ratios for output ripple current may also be computed.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] An electronic filter with high impedance at the ripple frequency may be used to reduce ripple voltage and increase or decrease DC output; such a filter is often called a smoothing filter.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The initial step in AC to DC conversion is to send the AC current through a rectifier.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The ripple voltage output is very large in this situation; the peak-to-peak ripple voltage is equal to the peak AC voltage minus the forward voltage of the rectifier diodes.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] In the case of an SS silicon diode, the forward voltage is 0.7 V; for vacuum tube rectifiers, forward voltage usually ranges between 25 and 67 V (5R4).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The output voltage is a sine wave with the negative half-cycles inverted.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Reducing ripple is only one of several principal considerations in power supply filter design.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The filtering of ripple voltage is analogous to filtering other kinds of signals.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] However, in AC/DC power conversion as well as DC power generation, high voltages and currents or both may be output as ripple.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Therefore, large discrete components like high ripple-current rated electrolytic capacitors, large iron-core chokes and wire-wound power resistors are best suited to reduce ripple to manageable proportions before passing the current to an IC component like a voltage regulator, or on to the load.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The kind of filtering required depends on the amplitude of the various harmonics of the ripple and the demands of the load.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] For example, a moving coil (MC) input circuit of a phono preamplifier may require that ripple be reduced to no more than a few hundred nanovolts (10−9V).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] In contrast, a battery charger, being a wholly resistive circuit, does not require any ripple filtering.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Since the desired output is direct current (essentially 0 Hz), ripple filters are usually configured as low pass filters characterized by shunt capacitors and series chokes.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Series resistors may replace chokes for reducing the output DC voltage, and shunt resistors may be used for voltage regulation.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Most power supplies are now switched mode designs.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The filtering requirements for such power supplies are much easier to meet owing to the high frequency of the ripple waveform.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The ripple frequency in switch-mode power supplies is not related to the line frequency, but is instead a multiple of the frequency of the chopper circuit, which is usually in the range of 50 kHz to 1 MHz.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A capacitor input filter (in which the first component is a shunt capacitor) and choke input filter (which has a series choke as the first component) can both reduce ripple, but have opposing effects on voltage and current, and the choice between them depends on the characteristics of the load.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Capacitor input filters have poor voltage regulation, so are preferred for use in circuits with stable loads and low currents (because low currents reduce ripple here).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Choke input filters are preferred for circuits with variable loads and high currents (since a choke outputs a stable voltage and higher current means less ripple in this case).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The number of reactive components in a filter is called its *order*.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Each reactive component reduces signal strength by 6 dB/octave above (or below for a high-pass filter) the corner frequency of the filter, so that a 2nd-order low-pass filter for example, reduces signal strength by 12 dB/octave above the corner frequency.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Resistive components (including resistors and parasitic elements like the DCR of chokes and ESR of capacitors) also reduce signal strength, but their effect is *linear*, and does not vary with frequency.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A common arrangement is to allow the rectifier to work into a large smoothing capacitor which acts as a reservoir.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] After a peak in output voltage the capacitor supplies the current to the load and continues to do so until the capacitor voltage has fallen to the value of the now rising next half-cycle of rectified voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] At that point the rectifier conducts again and delivers current to the reservoir until peak voltage is again reached.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] If the RC time constant is large in comparison to the period of the AC waveform, then a reasonably accurate approximation can be made by assuming that the capacitor voltage falls linearly.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A further useful assumption can be made if the ripple is small compared to the DC voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] In this case the phase angle through which the rectifier conducts will be small and it can be assumed that the capacitor is discharging all the way from one peak to the next with little loss of accuracy.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The current and time t is taken from start of capacitor discharge until the minimum voltage on a full wave rectified signal as shown on the figure to the right.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The time $t_{\text{ave}}$ would then be equal to half the period of the full wave input.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] For the RMS value of the ripple voltage, the calculation is more involved as the shape of the ripple waveform has a bearing on the result.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Assuming a sawtooth waveform is a similar assumption to the ones above.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The RMS value of a sawtooth wave is ${\frac {V_{\mathrm {p} }}{\sqrt {3}}}$ where $V_{\mathrm {p} }$ is peak voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Another approach to reducing ripple is to use a series choke.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A choke has a filtering action and consequently produces a smoother waveform with fewer high-order harmonics.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Against this, the DC output is close to the average input voltage as opposed to the voltage with the reservoir capacitor which is close to the peak input voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] This is a little less than 0.483 because higher-order harmonics were omitted from consideration.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] There is a minimum inductance (which is relative to the resistance of the load) required in order for a series choke to continuously conduct current.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] If the inductance falls below that value, current will be intermittent and output DC voltage will rise from the average input voltage to the peak input voltage; in effect, the inductor will behave like a capacitor.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] That minimum inductance, called the *critical inductance* is $L={\frac {R}{2\pi (3f)}}$ where R is the load resistance and f the line frequency.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] This gives values of L = R/1131 (often stated as R/1130) for 60 Hz mains rectification, and L = R/942 for 50 Hz mains rectification.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Additionally, interrupting current to an inductor will cause its magnetic flux to collapse exponentially; as current falls, a voltage spike composed of very high harmonics results which can damage other components of the power supply or circuit.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] This phenomenon is called flyback voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The complex impedance of a series choke is effectively part of the load impedance, so that lightly loaded circuits have increased ripple (just the opposite of a capacitor input filter).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] For that reason, a choke input filter is almost always part of an LC filter section, whose ripple reduction is independent of load current.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] In high voltage/low current circuits, a resistor may replace the series choke in an LC filter section (creating an RC filter section).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] This has the effect of reducing the DC output as well as ripple.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Similarly because of the independence of LC filter sections with respect to load, a reservoir capacitor is also commonly followed by one resulting in a low-pass Π-filter.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A Π-filter results in a much lower ripple factor than a capacitor or choke input filter alone.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] It may be followed by additional LC or RC filter sections to further reduce ripple to a level tolerable by the load.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] However, use of chokes is deprecated in contemporary designs for economic reasons.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A more common solution where good ripple rejection is required is to use a reservoir capacitor to reduce the ripple to something manageable and then pass the current through a voltage regulator circuit.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The regulator circuit, as well as providing a stable output voltage, will incidentally filter out nearly all of the ripple as long as the minimum level of the ripple waveform does not go below the voltage being regulated to.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Switched-mode power supplies usually include a voltage regulator as part of the circuit.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Voltage regulation is based on a different principle than filtering: it relies on the peak inverse voltage of a diode or series of diodes to set a maximum output voltage; it may also use one or more voltage amplification devices like transistors to boost voltage during sags.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Because of the non-linear characteristics of these devices, the output of a regulator is free of ripple.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] A simple voltage regulator may be made with a series resistor to drop voltage followed by a shunt zener diode whose Peak Inverse Voltage (PIV) sets the maximum output voltage; if voltage rises, the diode shunts away current to maintain regulation.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Ripple current is a periodic non-sinusoidal waveform derived from an AC power source characterized by high amplitude narrow bandwidth pulses.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The pulses coincide with peak or near peak amplitude of an accompanying sinusoidal voltage waveform.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Ripple current results in increased dissipation in parasitic resistive portions of circuits like ESR of capacitors, DCR of transformers and inductors, internal resistance of storage batteries.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The dissipation is proportional to the current squared times resistance (I2R).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The RMS value of ripple current can be many times the RMS of the load current.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Ripple in the context of the frequency domain refers to the periodic variation in insertion loss with frequency of a filter or some other two-port network.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Not all filters exhibit ripple, some have monotonically increasing insertion loss with frequency such as the Butterworth filter.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Common classes of filter which exhibit ripple are the Chebyshev filter, inverse Chebyshev filter and the Elliptical filter.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The ripple is not usually strictly linearly periodic as can be seen from the example plot.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] Other examples of networks exhibiting ripple are impedance matching networks that have been designed using Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The ripple of these networks, unlike regular filters, will never reach 0 dB at minimum loss if designed for optimum transmission across the passband as a whole.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] The amount of ripple can be traded for other parameters in the filter design.
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] For instance, the rate of roll-off from the passband to the stopband can be increased at the expense of increasing the ripple without increasing the order of the filter (that is, the number of components has stayed the same).
[src:power-supply-design/ripple-electrical] On the other hand, the ripple can be reduced by increasing the order of the filter while at the same time maintaining the same rate of roll-off.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A **voltage regulator** is a system designed to automatically maintain a constant voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] It may use a simple feed-forward design or may include negative feedback.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] It may use an electromechanical mechanism or electronic components.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Depending on the design, it may be used to regulate one or more AC or DC voltages.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Electronic voltage regulators are found in devices such as computer power supplies, where they stabilize the DC voltages used by the processor and other elements.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In automobile alternators and central power station generator plants, voltage regulators control the output of the plant.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In an electric power distribution system, voltage regulators may be installed at a substation or along distribution lines so that all customers receive steady voltage independent of how much power is drawn from the line.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A simple voltage regulator can be made from a resistor in series with a forward-biased diode (or series of diodes), forming a voltage divider of sorts.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Due to the logarithmic shape of diode V-I curves, the voltage across the diode changes only slightly due to changes in current drawn or changes in the input.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When precise voltage control and efficiency are not important, this design may be adequate.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Since the forward voltage of a diode is small, this kind of voltage regulator is only suitable for low-voltage regulated output.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When higher-voltage output is needed, a reverse-biased zener diode or a series of zener diodes may be employed.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Zener diode regulators make use of the zener diode's fixed reverse voltage, which can be quite large.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Feedback voltage regulators operate by comparing the actual output voltage to some fixed reference voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Any difference is amplified and used to control the regulation element in such a way as to reduce the voltage error.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] This forms a negative feedback control loop; increasing the open-loop gain tends to increase regulation accuracy but reduce stability.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Stability is the avoidance of oscillation, or ringing, during step changes in load or input voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] There will also be a trade-off between stability and the speed of the response to changes.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] However, many regulators have over-current protection, so that they will entirely stop sourcing current (or limit the current in some way) if the output current is too high, and some regulators may also shut down if the input voltage is outside a given range (see also: Crowbar (circuit)).
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In electromechanical regulators, voltage regulation is easily accomplished by coiling the sensing wire to make an electromagnet.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The magnetic field produced by the current attracts a moving ferrous core held back under spring tension or gravitational pull.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] As voltage increases, so does the current, strengthening the magnetic field produced by the coil and pulling the core towards the field.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The magnet is physically connected to a mechanical power switch, which opens as the magnet moves into the field.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] As voltage decreases, so does the current, releasing spring tension or the weight of the core and causing it to retract.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] This closes the switch and allows the power to flow once more.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The relay(s) modulated the width of a current pulse to regulate the voltage output of the generator by controlling the average field current in the rotating machine which determines strength of the magnetic field produced which determines the unloaded output voltage per rpm.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Capacitors are not used to smooth the pulsed voltage as described earlier.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The large inductance of the field coil stores the energy delivered to the magnetic field in an iron core so the pulsed field current does not result in as strongly pulsed a field.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Both types of rotating machine produce a rotating magnetic field that induces an alternating current in the coils in the stator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A generator uses a mechanical commutator, graphite brushes running on copper segments, to convert the AC produced into DC by switching the external connections at the shaft angle when the voltage would reverse.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] An alternator accomplishes the same goal using rectifiers that do not wear down and require replacement.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Modern designs now use *solid state* technology (transistors) to perform the same function that the relays perform in electromechanical regulators.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Electromechanical regulators are used for mains voltage stabilisation—see AC voltage stabilizers below.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Generators, as used in power stations, ship electrical power production, or standby power systems, will have automatic voltage regulators (AVR) to stabilize their voltages as the load on the generators changes.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The first AVRs for generators were electromechanical systems, but a modern AVR uses solid-state devices.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] An AVR is a feedback control system that measures the output voltage of the generator, compares that output to a set point, and generates an error signal that is used to adjust the excitation of the generator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] As the excitation current in the field winding of the generator increases, its terminal voltage will increase.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The AVR will control current by using power electronic devices; generally a small part of the generator's output is used to provide current for the field winding.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Where a generator is connected in parallel with other sources such as an electrical transmission grid, changing the excitation has more of an effect on the reactive power produced by the generator than on its terminal voltage, which is mostly set by the connected power system.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Where multiple generators are connected in parallel, the AVR system will have circuits to ensure all generators operate at the same power factor.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] AVRs on grid-connected power station generators may have additional control features to help stabilize the electrical grid against upsets due to sudden load loss or faults.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] This is an older type of regulator used in the 1920s that uses the principle of a fixed-position field coil and a second field coil that can be rotated on an axis in parallel with the fixed coil, similar to a variocoupler.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When the movable coil is positioned perpendicular to the fixed coil, the magnetic forces acting on the movable coil balance each other out and voltage output is unchanged.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Rotating the coil in one direction or the other away from the center position will increase or decrease voltage in the secondary movable coil.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] This type of regulator can be automated via a servo control mechanism to advance the movable coil position in order to provide voltage increase or decrease.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A braking mechanism or high-ratio gearing is used to hold the rotating coil in place against the powerful magnetic forces acting on the moving coil.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Electromechanical regulators called *voltage stabilizers* or *tap-changers*, have also been used to regulate the voltage on AC power distribution lines.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] These regulators operate by using a servomechanism to select the appropriate tap on an autotransformer with multiple taps, or by moving the wiper on a continuously variable auto transfomer.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] If the output voltage is not in the acceptable range, the servomechanism switches the tap, changing the turns ratio of the transformer, to move the secondary voltage into the acceptable region.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The controls provide a dead band wherein the controller will not act, preventing the controller from constantly adjusting the voltage ("hunting") as it varies by an acceptably small amount.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The **ferroresonant transformer**, **ferroresonant regulator** or **constant-voltage transformer** is a type of saturating transformer used as a voltage regulator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] These transformers use a tank circuit composed of a high-voltage resonant winding and a capacitor to produce a nearly constant average output voltage with a varying input current or varying load.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The circuit has a primary on one side of a magnet shunt and the tuned circuit coil and secondary on the other side.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Voltage regulation results from magnetic saturation in the portion of the core associated with the resonant winding and secondary.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The ferroresonant approach is attractive due to its lack of active components, relying on the square-loop magnetic characteristics of the core operating in saturation to absorb variations in average input voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Saturating transformers provide a simple rugged method to stabilize an AC power supply.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Older designs produced outputs with significant harmonic content.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Modern designs improve waveform quality, but the output is not an ideal sine wave.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The ferroresonant action is a flux limiter rather than a voltage regulator, but with a fixed supply frequency it can maintain an almost constant average output voltage even as the input voltage varies widely.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The ferroresonant transformers, which are also known as *constant-voltage transformers* (CVTs) or "ferros", are also good surge suppressors, as they provide high isolation and inherent short-circuit protection.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A ferroresonant transformer can operate with an input voltage range ±40% or more of the nominal voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Output power factor remains in the range of 0.96 or higher from half to full load.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Because it regenerates an output voltage waveform, output distortion, which is typically less than 4%, is independent of any input voltage distortion, including notching.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Efficiency at full load is typically in the range of 89% to 93%.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] However, at low loads, efficiency can drop below 60%.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The current-limiting capability also becomes a handicap when a CVT is used in an application with moderate to high inrush current, like motors, transformers or magnets.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In this case, the CVT has to be sized to accommodate the peak current, thus forcing it to run at low loads and poor efficiency.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Minimum maintenance is required, as transformers and capacitors can be very reliable.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Some units have included redundant capacitors to allow several capacitors to fail between inspections without any noticeable effect on the device's performance.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Output voltage varies about 1.2% for every 1% change in supply frequency.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] For example, a 2 Hz change in generator frequency, which is very large, results in an output voltage change of only 4%, which has little effect for most loads.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] It accepts 100% single-phase switch-mode power-supply loading without any requirement for derating, including all neutral components.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Input current distortion remains less than 8% THD even when supplying nonlinear loads with more than 100% current THD.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Drawbacks of CVTs are their larger size, audible humming sound, and the high heat generation caused by saturation.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Some ferroresonant transformer have active control.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Voltage regulators or stabilizers are used to compensate for voltage fluctuations in mains power.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Large regulators may be permanently installed on distribution lines.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Small portable regulators may be plugged in between sensitive equipment and a wall outlet.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Automatic voltage regulators on generator sets to maintain a constant voltage for changes in load.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The voltage regulator compensates for the change in load.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Power distribution voltage regulators normally operate on a range of voltages, for example 150–240 V or 90–280 V.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Many simple DC power supplies regulate the voltage using either series or shunt regulators, but most apply a voltage reference using a *shunt regulator* such as a Zener diode, avalanche breakdown diode, or voltage regulator tube.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The power supply is designed to only supply a maximum amount of current that is within the safe operating capability of the shunt regulating device.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] If the stabilizer must provide more power, the shunt output is only used to provide the standard voltage reference for the electronic device, known as the voltage stabilizer.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The voltage stabilizer is the electronic device, able to deliver much larger currents on demand.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Active regulators employ at least one active (amplifying) component such as a transistor or operational amplifier.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Shunt regulators are often (but not always) passive and simple, but always inefficient because they (essentially) dump the excess current which is not available to the load.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When more power must be supplied, more sophisticated circuits are used.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In the past, one or more vacuum tubes were commonly used as the variable resistance.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Modern designs like Shakti Servo use one or more transistors instead, perhaps within an integrated circuit.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Linear designs have the advantage of very "clean" output with little noise introduced into their DC output, but are most often much less efficient and unable to step-up or invert the input voltage like switched supplies.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] All linear regulators require a higher input than the output.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] If the input voltage approaches the desired output voltage, the regulator will "drop out".
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The input to output voltage differential at which this occurs is known as the regulator's drop-out voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Low-dropout regulators (LDOs) allow an input voltage that can be much lower (i.e., they waste less energy than conventional linear regulators).
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Entire linear regulators are available as integrated circuits.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] These chips come in either fixed or adjustable voltage types.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A switching regulator works similar to an appliance charger.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When battery charge is low, a charger is plugged in and energy is transferred to the battery.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When charge is high, the charger disables itself, or is unplugged.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A switching regulator nominally cycles hundreds to tens of thousands times per second automatically.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The duty cycle is controlled by a similar feedback mechanism as in a linear regulator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Because the series element is either fully conducting, or switched off, it dissipates almost no power; this is what gives the switching design its efficiency.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Switching regulators are also able to generate output voltages which are higher than the input, or of opposite polarity—something not possible with a linear design.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In switched regulators, the pass transistor is used as a "controlled switch" and is operated at either cutoff or saturated state.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Hence the power transmitted across the pass device is in discrete pulses rather than a steady current flow.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Greater efficiency is achieved since the pass device is operated as a low-impedance switch.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When the pass device is at cutoff, there is no current and it dissipates no power.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Again when the pass device is in saturation, a negligible voltage drop appears across it and thus dissipates only a small amount of average power, providing maximum current to the load.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In either case, the power wasted in the pass device is very little and almost all the power is transmitted to the load.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Thus the efficiency of a switched-mode power supply is remarkably high – in the range of 70–90%.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Switched mode regulators rely on pulse-width modulation to control the average value of the output voltage.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The average value of a repetitive-pulse waveform depends on the area under the waveform.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] When the duty cycle is varied, the average voltage changes proportionally.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Like linear regulators, nearly complete switching regulators are also available as integrated circuits (e.g.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Unlike linear regulators, these usually require an inductor for step-up or capacitor for step-down, that acts as the energy storage element.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The IC regulators combine the reference voltage source, error op-amp, and pass transistor with short-circuit current limiting and thermal-overload protection.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Switching regulators are more prone to input noise, output noise, and instability than linear regulators.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] However, they provide much better power efficiency than linear regulators.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Regulators powered from AC power circuits can use silicon controlled rectifiers (SCRs) as the series device.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Whenever the output voltage is below the desired value, the SCR is triggered, allowing electricity to flow into the load until the AC mains voltage passes through zero (ending the half cycle).
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] SCR regulators have the advantages of being both very efficient and very simple, but because they can not terminate an ongoing half cycle of conduction, they are not capable of very accurate voltage regulation in response to rapidly changing loads.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] An alternative is the SCR shunt regulator which uses the regulator output as a trigger.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Both series and shunt designs are noisy, but powerful, as the device has a low on resistance.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Many power supplies use more than one regulating method in series.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] For example, the output from a switching regulator can be further regulated by a linear regulator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The switching regulator accepts a wide range of input voltages and efficiently generates a (somewhat noisy) voltage slightly above the ultimately desired output.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] That is followed by a linear regulator that generates exactly the desired voltage and eliminates nearly all the noise generated by the switching regulator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Other designs may use an SCR regulator as the "pre-regulator", followed by another type of regulator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] An efficient way of creating a variable-voltage, accurate output power supply is to combine a multi-tapped transformer with an adjustable linear post-regulator.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] A simple transistor regulator will provide a relatively constant output voltage *U*out for changes in the voltage *U*in of the power source and for changes in load *R*L, provided that *U*in exceeds *U*out by a sufficient margin and that the power handling capacity of the transistor is not exceeded.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The output voltage of the stabilizer is equal to the Zener diode voltage minus the base–emitter voltage of the transistor, *U*Z − *U*BE, where *U*BE is usually about 0.7 V for a silicon transistor, depending on the load current.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] In this case, the operational amplifier drives the transistor with more current if the voltage at its inverting input drops below the output of the voltage reference at the non-inverting input.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] Using the voltage divider (R1, R2 and R3) allows choice of the arbitrary output voltage between Uz and Uin.
[src:power-supply-design/voltage-regulator] The output voltage can only be held constant within specified limits.
